# Prefer `type` over `interface`

Use `type` aliases for all object shapes, unions, and other type declarations. Do not use `interface` unless there is a concrete reason (e.g. declaration merging with an external library).

```ts
// ❌ BAD
interface ComponentManifest {
  name: string;
  url: string;
}
```

```ts
// ✅ GOOD
type ComponentManifest = {
  name: string;
  url: string;
};
```

Rationale: `type` is a superset of what `interface` can express (unions, intersections, mapped and conditional types), so using a single form keeps the codebase consistent and avoids arbitrary choices per file.

# Prefer `#private` over `private`

Use ECMAScript private fields and methods (`#name`) for all class-private members. Do not use the TypeScript `private` keyword.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
export class Runtime {
  private registry = new Map<string, MountFn>();
  private destroyed = false;

  private assertAlive(): void {
    if (this.destroyed) throw new Error("destroyed");
  }
}
```

```ts
// ✅ GOOD
export class Runtime {
  readonly #registry = new Map<string, MountFn>();
  #destroyed = false;

  #assertAlive(): void {
    if (this.#destroyed) throw new Error("destroyed");
  }
}
```

Rationale: `#private` is enforced at runtime (not just by the compiler), cannot be accessed via bracket notation or `Object.keys`, and is preserved across plain JS output. The `private` keyword disappears after compilation and is only advisory. Use `readonly` alongside `#` when the field should not be reassigned.
